            "id": "af57382502a04d1fbdeae",
            "questionText": "A radio antenna broadcasts electromagnetic waves at a frequency of $!$98.5 \\ MHz$!$. The signal travels through the atmosphere to a receiver located $!$50 \\ km$!$ away. Due to atmospheric conditions, there is a delay of $!$20 \\ \\mu s$!$ in the signal's arrival. Considering that electromagnetic waves are produced by accelerating charges and travel at the speed of light, calculate the phase difference between the emitted and received signal at the receiver.",
            "imageText": "",
            "steps": [
                {
                    "id": "092da3ffeeff4b0a865d5",
                    "stepText": "Let's start by identifying the formula that relates phase difference with frequency and time delay. Please select the correct formula for computing the phase difference ($!$\\Delta\\phi$!$) from the options below.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "0c3ff372-9bd8-4961-9294-ab325dbdc20e",
                        "ee8bb1a6-fd07-4f51-81ae-e388a2828537"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\Delta\\phi = 2\\pi f \\Delta t$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\Delta\\phi = f \\Delta t$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\Delta\\phi = 2\\pi \\frac{\\Delta t}{T}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
